message.content:
To calculate the Quick Ratio, we need to determine the ratio of "Quick Assets" to "Current Liabilities." 

Quick Assets typically include:
- Cash on Hand
- Bank Deposits
- Accounts Receivable
- Interest Receivable (if any)

Inventory is excluded because it may not be quickly convertible to cash.

Given data as of the end date: 2024-02-05

Step 1: Sum the Quick Assets:
- Cash on Hand = -1,980,427.60 (note the negative value, indicating a deficit)
- Bank Deposits = 385,137.69
- Accounts Receivable = 12,792,007.89
- Interest Receivable = 18,176.52

Total Quick Assets = (-1,980,427.60) + 385,137.69 + 12,792,007.89 + 18,176.52
= (-1,980,427.60 + 385,137.69) + 12,792,007.89 + 18,176.52
= (-1,595,289.91) + 12,792,007.89 + 18,176.52
= 11,196,717.98 + 18,176.52
= 11,214,894.50

Step 2: Current Liabilities:
- Taxes Payable = 1,015,922.54
- Accounts Payable = 0.00

Total Current Liabilities = 1,015,922.54

Step 3: Calculate the Quick Ratio:
Quick Ratio = Quick Assets / Current Liabilities
= 11,214,894.50 / 1,015,922.54
â‰ˆ 11.04
